{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17603925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17603925"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:45:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:45:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15788"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15788","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15788"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.08,0.08,0.54,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8479"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71483"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8479"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15788"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56992"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"8498"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20382"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20383"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71483"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA histological section of testicular tissue is being examined under light microscopy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly describes the histological appearance of Leydig cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Elongated cells with clear cytoplasm surrounding blood vessels","Flattened cells with dark nuclei forming the basement membrane","Small round cells with basophilic cytoplasm within seminiferous tubules","Large polygonal cells with eosinophilic cytoplasm located between seminiferous tubules","Columnar cells with microvilli lining the seminiferous tubules"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe histological description of Leydig cells is \u0027\u003Cstrong\u003Elarge polygonal cells with eosinophilic cytoplasm located between seminiferous tubules\u003C/strong\u003E.\u0027 They are found in clusters within the interstitial space and are responsible for testosterone production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall round cells with basophilic cytoplasm\u003C/strong\u003E describes spermatogonia. \u003Cstrong\u003EElongated cells with clear cytoplasm surrounding blood vessels\u003C/strong\u003E describes peritubular myoid cells. \u003Cstrong\u003EFlattened cells with dark nuclei\u003C/strong\u003E describes the appearance of peritubular cells. \u003Cstrong\u003EColumnar cells with microvilli\u003C/strong\u003E describes Sertoli cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELeydig cells can be identified by their distinctive polygonal shape, abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm (due to numerous mitochondria and smooth endoplasmic reticulum), and round nuclei with prominent nucleoli. Their location in the interstitial space between seminiferous tubules is also characteristic.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Leydig cells are large polygonal cells with eosinophilic cytoplasm and round nuclei found in the interstitial space between seminiferous tubules.","Leydig cells are the main source of testosterone production in males."],"references":["Zirkin BR, Papadopoulos V. Leydig cells: formation, function, and regulation. Biol Reprod. 2018 Jul 1;99(1):101-111. doi: 10.1093/biolre/ioy059. PMID: 29566165; PMCID: PMC6044347.","Zirkin BR. Where do adult Leydig cells come from? Biol Reprod. 2010 Jun;82(6):1019-20. doi: 10.1095/biolreprod.110.084111. Epub 2010 Mar 17. PMID: 20237331; PMCID: PMC6366154.","Aladamat N, Tadi P. Histology, Leydig Cells. [Updated 2022 Nov 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK556007/","Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56992"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15788"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56992"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T18:35:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T18:35:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8479"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71483"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":